One thing I’d intentionally design

I call it “meme surface area.”

Don’t force memes.

Create little hooks that people naturally play with.

Examples:

The name.

The mascot.

The sayings.

The sticker.

The patch.

The little hidden details.

People love discovering things.

⸻

One prediction

I think your eventual hat becomes more important than the gummies.

Seriously.

If someone sees:

“That guy has the Wild Hawg hat…”

…and it looks genuinely cool, that’s free advertising every day.

That’s why I’ve been pushing toward a patch/logo that stands on its own.

⸻

I still think the logo ends up looking less like an illustration and more like a military unit insignia or heritage outdoor brand.

Simple.

Bold.

Recognizable.

Something that looks equally at home on:

* a Richardson 112 hat,
* a Pelican case,
* a Yeti,
* a duck call lanyard,
* a sticker on a truck window,
* or a gummy bag sitting on a gas station shelf.

When a logo works across all of those without needing text, you’ve probably found something special.